### Online Fonts and Integration into a Website

**Online fonts** refer to fonts that are hosted on a remote server and can be accessed via the internet. They allow web designers to use a wide variety of typefaces without needing to have the font files installed on the user's device. This ensures consistent font rendering across different browsers and devices. One popular service for online fonts is **Google Fonts**, which provides a vast collection of free fonts that can easily be integrated into web projects.

### How to Use Google Fonts in an HTML Document

To use Google Fonts, follow these steps:

1. **Choose a Font**: Go to [Google Fonts](https://fonts.google.com/) and select a font you want to use.
2. **Get the Embed Code**: Click on the selected font and then click on the "+ Select this style" button. In the right sidebar, you will see an option to embed the font. Copy the provided `<link>` tag.
3. **Integrate into HTML**: Paste the `<link>` tag in the `<head>` section of your HTML document.

#### Example HTML Code Using Google Fonts

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Using Google Fonts</title>
    <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Roboto:wght@400;700&display=swap" rel="stylesheet"> <!-- Google Font Link -->
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: 'Roboto', sans-serif; /* Applying the Google Font */
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            color: #333;
            line-height: 1.6;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 20px;
        }
        
        h1 {
            font-size: 36px;
            font-weight: 700; /* Bold weight */
        }

        p {
            font-size: 18px;
            font-weight: 400; /* Normal weight */
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Using Google Fonts</h1>
    <p>This paragraph uses the Roboto font from Google Fonts. It demonstrates how to integrate online fonts into your website.</p>
</body>
</html>
```

### What is a Favicon?

A **favicon** (short for "favorite icon") is a small icon associated with a website. It is displayed in the browser's address bar, in browser tabs, and in bookmarks. A favicon helps users quickly identify your website among multiple open tabs and provides a more professional look.

### How to Add a Favicon to a Web Page

To add a favicon to your web page, follow these steps:

1. **Create or Obtain a Favicon**: The favicon should be a small square image, typically 16x16 or 32x32 pixels. Common formats include `.ico`, `.png`, or `.svg`.
2. **Upload the Favicon**: Place the favicon file in the root directory of your website or in a specific folder.
3. **Add the HTML Code**: Include a `<link>` tag in the `<head>` section of your HTML document to reference the favicon file.

#### Example HTML Code Adding a Favicon

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Page with Favicon</title>
    <link rel="icon" href="favicon.ico" type="image/x-icon"> <!-- Favicon Link -->
    <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Roboto:wght@400;700&display=swap" rel="stylesheet">
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: 'Roboto', sans-serif;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            color: #333;
            line-height: 1.6;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 20px;
        }
        
        h1 {
            font-size: 36px;
            font-weight: 700;
        }

        p {
            font-size: 18px;
            font-weight: 400;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Page with Favicon</h1>
    <p>This page has a favicon and uses Google Fonts for styling.</p>
</body>
</html>
```

### Summary

- **Online Fonts**: Fonts hosted on the internet, allowing consistent styling across devices.
- **Using Google Fonts**: Choose a font from Google Fonts, copy the embed code, and use it in your HTML document.
- **Favicon**: A small icon representing your website, added via a `<link>` tag in the HTML `<head>` section. 

Both online fonts and favicons enhance the appearance and branding of a website, contributing to a better user experience.